                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-05-04T01:34:20.450-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-05-08T10:04:58.700-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Challenges in measuring the disease’s impact"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-05-04T01:34:55.885-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-08-18T15:41:33.998-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>It is estimated that up to 10% of adults and 25% of children live with atopic dermatitis globally, although those rates vary by location.&amp;nbsp;&lt;sup>2, 3&lt;/sup>&amp;nbsp;Between 20 and 46 percent of adults with atopic dermatitis have moderate to severe disease.&lt;sup>4&lt;/sup>&amp;nbsp;That’s a fairly high number of patients. Yet many people have never heard of this condition, and treatment options remain somewhat limited.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Atopic dermatitis isn’t always diagnosed accurately or in a timely fashion due to a variety of factors, including where a person lives or the type of physician he or she visits. These variables have led to a lack of or inconsistent data about the true global burden of AD, including how widespread it is and how it affects different populations in unique ways. That information could hold critical clues for scientists who are developing treatments for the disease.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Still, despite the gaps in information about atopic dermatitis, the scientific community has made great strides toward improving care for people who are living with this challenging disease.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
