                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Examining the daily experience of atopic dermatitis"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-05-04T01:34:55.885-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-12-21T01:40:06.948-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>The difficult reality of living with atopic dermatitis, for patients, is what drives many scientists and researchers to expand their knowledge of the disease and uncover its biological mechanism.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Imagine waking up in your bed and seeing blood on your sheets because you were scratching relentlessly in your sleep – or not being able to sleep at all because it feels like you’re lying on a bed of thorns. Think about being on a date, or having dinner with your partner, and trying to explain a flare-up you’re having at that moment.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>People around you might be afraid that you’re contagious. Because your skin is so sensitive and irritated, it might require daily extensive routines of applying emollients, moisturizers, and other topical treatments. The logistical, social, and emotional issues linked to living with moderate to severe atopic dermatitis can make daily activities harder and make living a “normal” life nearly impossible.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“What we have heard from people with atopic dermatitis and the physicians who treat them is that those with moderate to severe disease are uncomfortable and may even have difficulty sleeping because of symptoms of their condition,” added Dr. Pangan. “Research has also shown that people with AD can feel embarrassed or ashamed of how their skin looks – leading to lower self-esteem and self-confidence.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
